@node Introduction "Introduction"
	In december 1994 I bought a CD³² (the last in stock).  But I didn't
want  it  just to play games.  In fact, I just wanted an AGA machine with a
CD-ROM  and  I  found that a CD³² + SX-1 is cheaper than an A1200 + CD-ROM.
After  that,  I  purchassed  a  SX-1 in England.  Well, my machine was very
powerful  but  there was a problem.  The PSU is just too weak.  Putting two
disk drives did just break it.
	Now  I  would say to Commodore (even if now you're doing PC's) that
the  PSU who came with the CD³² is a muthaf#?cking PSU.  It is too weak and
that's  not  all.   It  hasn't  got a fuse, it's impossible to open and the
cables  are  not  coloured  logically.   An  it's  very weight!!!  So Amiga
Technologies please, change this PSU.  Use the old good A500 PSU.
	Well.   My  PSU was broken.  So I decided to build another one (but
with  much  more power).  I searched trought Internet a documentation about
the plug of the CD³² but...  nothing!!
	Fortunately,  a  friend  called BAP did send me his CD³² PSU.  So I
tested  it  and  finally  my  CD³²  is  working with a PC PSU (and it works
well!!).   If you're a owner of a CD-32 and a SX-1, I think it's better you
make a more powerful PSU to avoid problems.

	Let's go!!!!!
@endnode
 
