@node material "What you need"
For doing this project, you need:

		- Some screwdrivers

		- A PC-style PSU

		- The original CD³²'s PSU

		- A soldering-iron

		- Something to cut the cables

		- A multimeter (optional)

		- A insulate ribbon

		- And a clean desk

	That's all!!!
@endnode

@node build "Building the Power Supply Unit"
	Before  starting, remember that you'll need to cut the cable of the
CD³²'s PSU.  Doing that will invalidate the warranty, so make your choice.

	Well,  you  need  a  PC PSU.  They are powerful, reliable and don't
overheat because they are fan cooled (it will make a bit of noise, but...).
You can take a PC, open it, take his PSU and get rid of it.  The PSU is the
only  good think the PCs have.  Look at the PSU.  There is a lot of cables.
You  need  only 3 cables.  The +5V, the +12V and the GND.  In the PC-XT the
+5V is the red cable, the +12V the yellow and the GND the black cable.

Remove  the  PSU  of  the PC.  You only need to remove some screws.  If you
don't have any PSU, you can buy one.  They're not too expensive.

After  that,  look  at the PSU's connectors.  There are 2 or more 5¼ drives
connectors.   Take  one  and  cut  the four cables 2 centimeters behind the
plug.

Now,  strip  one  centimeter  of  each  cables  and solder the 2 GND cables
together (the black ones).

Take  the  CD³²'s PSU and open it with a good screwdriver(you need to break
the plastic sheet under the box).  Cut the 4 cables (red, yellow, black and
brown)  and remove the PSU to CD³² cable.  Solder the red and yellow cables
together.

It's  time  to join the PC-PSU to the CD³².  Solder each PSU cable with the
good cable of the CD³² plug.  Refere to the diagram below:

	PC-PSU			CD³² CABLE		VOLTAGE
	------			----------		-------
	black	==============	black			GND
	red	==============	yellow and red		+5V
	yellow	==============	brown			+12V


Insulate  all  the  cables  with  rubber.   It's  very  important  to avoid
short-circuits.

If  you've  got a multimeter, control the voltage (be careful, it's easy to
touch more than one pin on the CD³²'s cable plug).

Insulate the others PC-PSU's cables.

Double check all.  If you made a mistake, you can damage the CD³².

That's  it.   Plug  the PSU, turn it on and turn the CD³² on.  It will work
fine now.  If not, you made a mistake and your CD³² is certainly broken.


Now  you  can  add as much drives, harddisks and boards you like.  A PC PSU
can  cope with all.  For example, here is a comparison between the original
CD³²'s PSU and my PC-PSU.

	CD³²'s PSU				PC-PSU
	----------				------
	+12V = 0.5A				+12V = 5.5A
	+5V  = 2.2A				+5V  = 15A


If you want, you can also plug your monitor in the PSU's AC OUTLET.

A scheme is supplied in the archive if you need more informations.
@endnode

